President Obama released a statement on the 50th anniversary of the Civil Rights Act of 1964. He highlighted the significance of this legislation in shaping the national identity of the United States. The Civil Rights Act prohibited discrimination based on race, color, religion, sex, or national origin, effectively ending segregation in schools, workplaces, and public facilities. It also paved the way for other important acts such as the Voting Rights Act and the Fair Housing Act. President Obama emphasized that although progress has been made over the past 50 years, there is still work to be done in tearing down barriers and ensuring equal opportunity for all Americans. He encouraged a commitment to making America more just, equal, and free.